ays = 38.0\n|source 1 = India Meteorological Department (record high and low up to 2010)<ref name= IMD >\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/extreme/meerut2.htm\n| title = Meerut Climatological Table Period: 1971\u20132000\n| publisher = [[India Meteorological Department]]\n| accessdate = April 15, 2015\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140214130716/http://www.imd.gov.in/section/climate/extreme/meerut2.htm\n| archive-date = 14 February 2014\n| url-status = live\n| df = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref><ref name=IMD2>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf \n |title=Ever recorded Maximum and minimum temperatures up to 2010 \n |publisher=India Meteorological Department \n |accessdate=April 15, 2015 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316064314/http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf\n |archivedate=16 March 2014\n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> \n|date=April 2015}}\n\n==Geography==\n{{For|description of the geography of the district|Meerut district#Geography}}\nMeerut is the largest city in [[National Capital Region (India)|NCR]] after Delhi.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}} Meerut lies between the plains of the [[Ganges]] and those of the [[Yamuna]]. In area Meerut district covers 2,522&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (974 sq mi), which is larger than Delhi (Delhi covers an area of 1,484&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> [573 sq mi]). However, Meerut's population is three times less than that of Delhi (Current population of Meerut is 3,443,689).\n\n== Administration ==\n\n=== General Administration ===\n[[Meerut division]] which consists of seven districts, and is headed by the [[Divisional Commissioner]] of Meerut, who is an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS officer]] of high seniority, the [[Divisional Commissioner|Commissioner]] is the head of local government institutions (including Municipal Corporations) in the division, is in charge of infrastructural development in his division and is also responsible for maintaining law and order in the division.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|title=CONSTITUTIONAL SETUP|website=[[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]|access-date=August 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831000649/http://up.gov.in/upconstitution.aspx|archive-date=31 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":422\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration (6th Edition)|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=563\u2013572}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=26\u2013129}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=5.1\u20135.2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yourarticlelibrary.com/india-2/role-and-functions-of-divisional-commissioner/46672/|title=Role and Functions of Divisional Commissioner|date=6 January 2015|website=Your Article Library|access-date=August 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816065354/http://www.yourarticlelibrary.com/india-2/role-and-functions-of-divisional-commissioner/46672/|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[District collector|District Magistrate]] of Meerut reports to the [[Divisional Commissioner]]. The current Commissioner is Anita Meshram.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://meerutdivision.nic.in/index_en.html|title=Office of the Divisional Commissioner, Meerut Division|website=Office of the [[Divisional Commissioner]], Meerut|access-date=August 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807232157/http://meerutdivision.nic.in/index_en.html|archive-date=7 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meerut.nic.in/geninfo/commr.htm|title=Commissioners of Meerut Division|website=Meerut District|access-date=August 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811215319/http://meerut.nic.in/geninfo/commr.htm|archive-date=11 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMeerut district administration is headed by the [[District Collector|District Magistrate]] of Meerut, who is an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS officer]]. The [[District Collector|DM]] is in charge of property records and revenue collection for the central government and oversees the [[Elections in India|elections]] held in the city. The [[District collector|DM]] is also responsible for maintaining law and order in the city, hence the SSP of Meerut also reports to the [[District Collector|DM]] of Meerut.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Indian Administration (6th Edition)|last=Maheshwari|first=S.R.|publisher=Orient Blackswan Private Ltd.|year=2000|isbn=9788125019886|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=573\u2013597}}</ref><ref name=\":63\">{{Cite book|title=Governance in India (2nd Edition)|last=Laxmikanth|first=M.|publisher=McGraw Hill Education|year=2014|isbn=978-9339204785|location=[[Noida]]|pages=6.1\u20136.6}}</ref><ref name=\":53\">{{Cite book|title=Revenue administration in India: A case study of Bihar|last=Singh|first=G.P.|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1993|isbn=978-8170993810|location=[[Delhi]]|pages=50\u2013124}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.importantindia.com/1724/powers-of-district-magistrate-in-india/|title=Powers Of District Magistrate in India|website=Important India|accessdate=August 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816062201/http://www.importantindia.com/1724/powers-of-district-magistrate-in-india/|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The district is subdivided into three [[tehsil]]s, namely Meerut, Mawana and Sardhana, each headed by a [[Sub-Divisional Magistrate]]. The tehsils are further divided into 12 blocks.<ref name=\"msme\">{{cite web|url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/Meerut.pdf|title=Brief Industrial Profile of District Meerut|author=MSME-Development Institute, Agra|publisher=Ministry of Micro, Small & Medium Enterprises, Govt. of India|accessdate=12 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125001151/http://www.dcmsme.gov.in/dips/Meerut.pdf|archive-date=25 January 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The current District Magistrate of Meerut is Anil Dhingra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meerut.nic.in/geninfo/dm.htm|title=District Magistrates of Meerut|website=Meerut District|access-date=August 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811214824/http://meerut.nic.in/geninfo/dm.htm|archive-date=11 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Police Administration ===\nMeerut district comes under Meerut police zone and Meerut police range of [[Uttar Pradesh Police]]. Meerut zone is headed by an [[Indian Police Service|IPS officer]] in the rank of [[Additional director general of police|Additional Director General of Police]] (ADG), whereas Meerut range is headed by an [[Indian Police Service|IPS officer]] in the rank of [[Inspector-general of police|Inspector General of Police]] (IG). The Current ADG, Meerut Zone is Prashant Kumar,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?zonemrt&cd=OAAzADIA|title=Officers posted at Meerut Zone|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|access-date=August 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813193628/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?zonemrt&cd=OAAzADIA|archive-date=13 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> whereas the current IG, Meerut Range is Ram Kumar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?rangemrt&cd=OAA3ADEA|title=Officers posted at Meerut Range|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|access-date=August 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813193546/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?rangemrt&cd=OAA3ADEA|archive-date=13 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDistrict Police of Meerut is headed by the [[Superintendent of police (India)|Senior Superintendent of Police]] (SSP) who is an [[Indian Police Service|IPS]] officer and is accountable to the District Magistrate for Law and Order enforcement. He is assisted by four [[Superintendent of police (India)|Superintendents of Police]] (SP)/[[Additional superintendent of police|Additional Superintendent of Police]] (Addl. SP) (City, Rural Area, Traffic and Crime). The Meerut district is divided into numerous police circles, each headed by a Circle Officer in the rank of [[Deputy superintendent of police|Deputy Superintendent of Police]]. SP (Traffic) and SP (Crime) are assisted by one Circle Officer in the rank of Deputy Superintendent of Police each.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?meerut&cd=OQAzADAA|title=Officers posted at Meerut|website=[[Uttar Pradesh Police]]|access-date=August 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816113542/https://uppolice.gov.in/frmOfficials.aspx?meerut&cd=OQAzADAA|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The current SSP is Akhilesh kumar.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Infrastructure and Civic Administration ===\nThe development of infrastructure in the city is overseen by the Meerut Development Authority (MDA), which comes under the Housing Department of [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]]. The [[Divisional Commissioner]] of Meerut acts as the ''ex-officio'' Chairman of MDA, whereas a Vice-Chairman, a government-appointed [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS officer]], looks after the daily matters of the authority. The current Vice-Chairman of Meerut Development Authority is Sita Ram Yadav.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdameerut.in/telephone-directory/|title=Telephone Directory|website=Meerut Development Authority|access-date=August 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816114653/http://mdameerut.in/telephone-directory/|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe city is administered by [[Meerut Municipal Corporation]], which is responsible for performing civic administrative functions administered by Municipal Commissioner (PCS Officer) whereas Mayor is ceremonial head of the Corporation. The current Municipal Commissioner of Meerut Municipal Corporation is [[Manoj Kumar Chauhan (Indian civil servant)|Manoj Kumar Chauhan]].\n\n=== Central Government Offices ===\nThe office of the Chief Commissioner, Customs & Central Excise, Meerut Zone, has jurisdiction over 13 districts of Uttrakhand and 14 districts of Uttar Pradesh. This jurisdiction was carved out of the Lucknow Zone. It comprises the erstwhile Customs & Central Excise Commissionerates of Meerut & Noida. The Meerut Commissionerate was bifurcated into two Commissionerates, namely, \u2018Meerut-I and Ghaziabad\u2019 and the Noida Commissionerate was bifurcated into \u2018Noida and Meerut-II\u2019. In addition, jurisdiction of Central Excise Division Bareilly was included in the jurisdiction of Meerut-II Commissionerate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cxmeerutzone.gov.in/aboutus.htm|title=Customs, Central Excise and Service Tax Meerut Zone: About Us|accessdate=5 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613143614/http://cxmeerutzone.gov.in/aboutus.htm|archive-date=13 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nCGHS department of Meerut provides comprehensive health care facilities for the central govt employees and pensioners and their dependents residing in this city.\n\n==Meerut Cantonment==\n[[File:Mall Road Meerut Cantt.jpg|right|thumb|Mall Road in Meerut Cantonment]]\n\nMeerut Cantonment was established by the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] in 1803 after the [[Battle of Laswari]]. It is the one of the largest cantonment of India both in land area {{Convert|3568.06|hectare|sqkm|2|abbr=on}} and population of 93684 (civil + military) people as per 2011 census).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbmrt.org.in/introduction/profile/profile_history.html|title=Welcome To Meerut Cantonment Board|website=www.cbmrt.org.in|access-date=2017-06-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517212818/http://cbmrt.org.in/introduction/profile/profile_history.html|archive-date=17 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Indian Rebellion of 1857#Meerut|Revolt of 1857]] started from \"Kali Paltan\" in Meerut Cantonment and Indian soldiers stationed here actively participated in the rebellion.<ref name=\"CDPcityprofile\">{{Harvnb|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 3.0 - City Profile, p. 37}}</ref><ref name=cbh/> The cantonment surrounds the old city from 3 sides \u2013 from Pallavpuram to Sainik Vihar to Ganga Nagar.{{Sfn|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 5 - SWOT Analysis, Section 5.2 - Weakness, p. 57}} It is well connected with the rest of country by roads as well as by rail. The Delhi Niti Paas Road (State Highway No. 45) passes through Meerut Cantonment.<ref name=cbh>{{cite web|title=Meerut Cantonment: Historical Background|url=http://cbmeerut.org.in/index.html|accessdate=8 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180408/http://cbmeerut.org.in/index.html|archive-date=21 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Meerut cantonment was the divisional headquarters of the [[7th (Meerut) Division]] of the [[British Indian Army]] from 1829 to 1920.\n\nSoldiers from the cantonment have actively participated in the [[First Battle of Ypres]], both the [[First Battle of El Alamein|1st]] and [[Second Battle of El Alamein|2nd]] Battles of El Alamein, [[Battle of France]], [[Burma Campaign]], the [[Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|Indo-Pakistani Wars]], [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] and [[Kargil War]].{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nIt has been the regimental center of [[Punjab Regiment (India)|Punjab Regiment]] [[Indian Army Corps of Signals|Corps of Signals]], [[Jat Regiment]], [[Sikh Regiment]] and [[Dogra Regiment]].{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Under-Construction Flyover on NH-58 Sardhana Road Crossing in Meerut.jpg|right|thumb|Atop an under-construction overpass]]\nMeerut is the 63rd-fastest-growing urban area in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth1.html|title=City Mayors: World's fastest growing urban areas (1)|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125090345/http://citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth1.html|archive-date=25 November 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is the 14th fastest developing city in India. A June 2011 report by US financial services firm [[Morgan Stanley]] gave Meerut the 5th spot on the \"vibrancy\" index, ahead of Delhi and Mumbai.<ref name=mss>{{cite web|url=http://linkback.morganstanley.com/web/sendlink/webapp/BMServlet?file=p8nqjstu-3o4l-g000-bf29-d8d3855ac300&store=0&user=du2n7fso2h1-35&__gda__=1434119633_42de03d0250c5e68f10b338c6d0f6df6 |publisher=morgan stanley |title=MORGAN STANLEY AlphaWise City Vibrancy Index: A Guide to India's Urbanization |accessdate=12 November 2012 |pages=15 |format=pdf |date=June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106173608/http://linkback.morganstanley.com/web/sendlink/webapp/BMServlet?file=p8nqjstu-3o4l-g000-bf29-d8d3855ac300&store=0&user=du2n7fso2h1-35&__gda__=1434119633_42de03d0250c5e68f10b338c6d0f6df6 |archivedate=6 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Meerut ranked second on both the financial penetration index, which measures things like the presence of ATMs and bank branches, and on the consumption index, indicating the city's transformation into an urban town. While the city ranked in the bottom 10 in job creations, the report suggests that overall there are plenty of signs of \"potential for urbanisation,\" including future employment opportunities.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2011/06/15/why-meerut-is-more-vibrant-than-mumbai/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Diksha | last=Sahni | title=Why Meerut is More Vibrant Than Mumbai | date=15 June 2011 | access-date=4 August 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316045416/http://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2011/06/15/why-meerut-is-more-vibrant-than-mumbai/ | archive-date=16 March 2017 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The infrastructure segment of Meerut is currently going through a boom phase with many new projects coming up in and around the city.<ref name=credai>{{cite web|title=Realty Boom in Meerut \u2013 Credai-NCR|url=http://credaincr.org/archive_news_details.php?nid=8631&m=1&y=2011|publisher=credaincr.org|accessdate=11 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814020439/http://credaincr.org/archive_news_details.php?nid=8631&m=1&y=2011|archive-date=14 August 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=toi2>{{cite web|title=Realty Boom in Meerut|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=CAP/2011/01/08&PageLabel=53&EntityId=Ar05300&ViewMode=HTML&GZ=T|work=Times of India|location=India|accessdate=11 April 2011|date=8 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829212553/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=CAP%2F2011%2F01%2F08&PageLabel=53&EntityId=Ar05300&ViewMode=HTML&GZ=T|archive-date=29 August 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are many new buildings, shopping complexes, malls, roads, flyovers and apartments coming up. The Upper Ganga Canal Expressway is also under development.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} On the [[India City Competitiveness Index]], the city ranked 45th in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://competitiveness.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/City-Competitiveness-Report-2010-Businessworld.pdf|title=Boulevards of Dreams|publisher=Businessworld|author=Srikant Srinivas|author2=Amit Kapoor|date=13 December 2010|access-date=4 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106175113/http://competitiveness.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/City-Competitiveness-Report-2010-Businessworld.pdf|archive-date=6 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 37th in 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-indias-50-most-competitive-cities/20111213.htm#26|title=India's 50 most Competitive cities|publisher=Rediff|date=13 December 2011|accessdate=6 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106203709/http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-indias-50-most-competitive-cities/20111213.htm#26|archive-date=6 January 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and 39th in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://competitiveness.in/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/India_City_Competitiveness_Index_2012_Rank.pdf|title=Ranks of 50 Cities as per the India City Competitiveness Index 2012|publisher=Institute of Competitiveness, India|access-date=4 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021183840/http://competitiveness.in/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/India_City_Competitiveness_Index_2012_Rank.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Industry===\n[[File:Book Cover of Sangeet Puranmal Ka.jpg|thumb|right|The cover of the book ''Sangeet Puranmal Ka'' (lit. The Music of Puranmal) by Ramlal. The book was published in 1879 from the city.]]\nMeerut is one of the important industrial towns of western Uttar Pradesh with several traditional and modern industries.<ref name=ch3/> It is traditionally known for [[Loom|handloom]] works and [[scissors]] industry.<ref name=\"CDPeconomicbase\">{{Harvnb|CDP|2006|loc=Executive Summary, Section 3.1.3 - Economic Base, p. 15}}</ref> Meerut was one of the first cities in northern India where publishing was set up during the 19th century. It was a major center of [[Publishing|commercial publishing]] during the 1860s and 1870s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Print areas: book history in India|author=Swapan Chakravorty, Abhijit Gupta, [[Jadavpur University]] Department of English|publisher=Orient Blackswan|year=2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lKQPnCIZMnIC|accessdate=3 February 2012|isbn=978-81-7824-082-4}}</ref>\n\nMeerut is a rich agricultural area, which also contains land that is not suitable for harvest.. Being in the proximity of Delhi, it is ideal for industry. It is home to 520 micro, small and medium scale industries.<ref name=did>{{cite web|url=http://meerut.nic.in/did_260810.pdf|title=Industrial Directory, District-Meerut|publisher=Meerut Official Website|page=29|accessdate=28 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180552/http://meerut.nic.in/did_260810.pdf|archive-date=21 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> {{As of|August 2006}}, Meerut has about 23,471 industrial units, including 15,510 small-scale units and 7,922 cottage industries.{{Sfn|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 3 - City Profile, Section 3.5.1 - Industries, p. 46}}\n\nExisting industries in the city include tyres, textile, transformer, sugar, distillery, chemical, engineering, paper, publishing, and sports goods manufacture.<ref name=\"CDPeconomicbase\"/>{{Sfn|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 1 - Indtroduction, Section 1.1 - Background, p. 31}}<ref name=did/> Prospective industries include [[Information technology|IT]] and [[ITES]].{{Sfn|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 5 - SWOT Analysis, Section 5.3 - Opportunity, p. 58}}\n\n[[UP State Industrial Development Corporation|Uttar Pradesh State Industrial Development Corporation]] (UPSIDC) has two industrial estates in the city, namely [[Partapur, Uttar Pradesh|Partapur]] and Udyog Puram.<ref name=upsidc1>{{cite web|title=Industrial Area Description \u2013 UPSIDC|url=http://upsidc.com/search_action3.php?name=Meerut&ind_area=Udyog+Puram&Submit2=Submit|publisher=UPSIDC|accessdate=9 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108214639/http://upsidc.com/search_action3.php?name=Meerut&ind_area=Udyog+Puram&Submit2=Submit|archive-date=8 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=upsidc2>{{cite web|title=Industrial Area Description \u2013 UPSIDC|url=http://upsidc.com/search_action3.php?name=Meerut&ind_area=Partapur&Submit2=Submit|publisher=UPSIDC|accessdate=9 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108213136/http://upsidc.com/search_action3.php?name=Meerut&ind_area=Partapur&Submit2=Submit|archive-date=8 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Revenue generation===\nMeerut has shown healthy numbers in terms of revenue generation. In 2005\u201306, Meerut occupied the fifth slot and contributed Rs 10,306 crore to the direct tax collection. It slipped to number six in 2006\u201307 when the revenue collection at Rs 11,203 crore was 18% lower than the target of Rs 13,627 crore. According to statistics compiled by the Income Tax department, Meerut contributed a Rs.10,089 crore to the national treasury in 2007/08, overall it was ranked 9th outperforming Lucknow, Jaipur, Bhopal, Kochi and Bhubaneshwar.<ref name=toi>{{cite news|title=Meerut 9th in top 10 tax-paying cities|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-07-01/india/27888870_1_direct-tax-collection-revenue-collection-meerut|work=The Times of India|location=India|accessdate=3 July 2011|date=1 July 2008|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120724190657/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-07-01/india/27888870_1_direct-tax-collection-revenue-collection-meerut|archive-date=24 July 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Air===\nThe nearest airport is the [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]] which is about 100&nbsp; km away.\n\nThe [[Meerut Airport|Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar Airport]] is located at [[Partapur, Uttar Pradesh|Partapur]]. It was proposed by the state government that the airstrip be converted to an international airport to reduce pressure on Delhi airport.<ref name=air>{{cite news|title=UP for Meerut Airport, Greater Noida Realty may skid|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-23/delhi/28135312_1_land-rates-greater-noida-airport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402010101/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010%2D02%2D23/delhi/28135312_1_land%2Drates%2Dgreater%2Dnoida%2Dairport|work=Times of India |location=India|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Lalit Kumar|archivedate=2 April 2010|page=1|format=XHTML 1.0 Transitional|url-status=dead|date=23 February 2010}}</ref> However, Plans to expand the Domestic airport were called off after protests against land acquisition started in other parts of the state.<ref>{{cite web|title= Maya govt scraps plan to expand Meerut airstrip|url= http://www.financialexpress.com/news/maya-govt-scraps-plan-to-expand-meerut-airstrip/673405/|access-date= 6 July 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140415191013/http://www.financialexpress.com/news/maya-govt-scraps-plan-to-expand-meerut-airstrip/673405|archive-date= 15 April 2014|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Following an accident in May 2012, the city administration barred private flights from using the airstrip.<ref>{{cite news |title= Meerut admin bars private flights from Partapur airstrip| url=http://www.business-standard.com/generalnews/news/meerut-admin-bars-private-flightspartapur-airstrip/9510/| newspaper=Business Standard India| date=16 May 2012| last1=India| first1=Press Trust of}}</ref>\n\n===Road===\nBy road Meerut is well-connected to major cities like [[Delhi]], [[Noida]], [[Faridabad]], [[Ghaziabad, India|Ghaziabad]], [[Haridwar]], etc. A large number of people commute to Delhi, Noida, Greater Noida, Ghaziabad and Gurgaon every day for work. Three national highways ([[National Highway 58 (India)|NH-58]], [[National Highway 119 (India)|NH-119]] & [[National Highway 235 (India)|NH-235]]) pass through Meerut. [[Upper Ganga Canal Expressway]] which passes through outskirts of the city is under development.\n\nThere are 2 main [[Bus station|bus terminals]], namely Bhainsali bus terminal and Sohrab Gate bus terminal from where [[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation]] (UPSRTC) buses ply to cities all over the state and all nearby cities. A [[JNNURM]] scheme was put in place.<ref name=\"CDPintroduction\">{{Harvnb|CDP|2006|loc=Executive Summary, Section 1.0 - Introduction, p. 13}}</ref> [[Low-floor bus|Low Floor]] City Buses (under JNNURM),{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} Normal City Buses, auto rickshaws and rickshaws are convenient public transport options to commute within the city.{{Sfn|CDP|2006|loc=Chapter 6 - Urban Infrastructure, Section 6.6.5 - Transportation systems in the City, p. 74}} Many new transport infrastructure projects like inner ring road, outer ring road and construction of new flyovers are proposed.{{Sfn|CMP|loc=Proposed Mobility Corridors, p. 12}}{{Sfn|CMP|loc=Road Over Bridges, p. 32}}\n\n;Delhi-Meerut Expressway (Under Construction)\n;{{Main|Delhi\u2013Meerut Expressway}}\nDelhi\u2013Meerut Expressway is an under-construction 90&nbsp;km long [[Controlled-access highway|controlled-access expressway]], connecting [[Delhi]] with Meerut via [[Dasna]] in [[Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh|Ghaziabad]] in India. While the present stretch of [[National Highway 24 (India)|National Highway 24]] (NH-24) up to Uttar Pradesh Gate will be widened to 14 lanes from the present 8, the road between UP Gate and Dasna will also be fourteen-laned. According to [[NHAI]] the entire construction work has been divided into three stages. The first stage will be from Delhi to Dasna (km 0 to km 27.5, 14 lanes), while the second stage will be from Dasna to Hapur (km 27.5 to km 49.9) on NH-24 (8 lanes). The third stage will include the construction of a 37&nbsp; km long new alignment, a green-field alignment, from Dasna to Meerut (6 lanes).\n\nPrime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] laid the foundation stone for expressway on December 31, 2015.\n\n===Railways===\n[[Image:Meerut City.jpg|thumb|150px|Meerut City Junction]]\nMeerut lies on the [[Delhi\u2013Meerut\u2013Saharanpur line|Delhi\u2013Saharanpur]] electrified railway line<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ghaziabad-saharanpur-rail-route-electrified-railways-116031600922_1.html|title=Ghaziabad-Saharanpur rail route electrified: Railways|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2016-03-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-06-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622224717/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ghaziabad-saharanpur-rail-route-electrified-railways-116031600922_1.html|archive-date=22 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has five railway stations: [[Meerut City railway station|Meerut City]], [[Meerut Cantt railway station|Meerut Cantt]], [[Partapur, Uttar Pradesh|Partapur]], Mohiuddinpur and Pabli Khas. Meerut City railway station is the busiest. The railway line between Delhi and Meerut was constructed in 1864<ref name=\"kinship\"/> and the Meerut Cantt station, which serves as a secondary railway station was founded in 1865.\n\nAbout 20,000 passengers travel daily to Delhi and back. Around 27 pairs of trains run between Meerut and Delhi, and four between Meerut and [[Khurja Junction railway station|Khurja]]. Two trains are available for Lucknow daily, namely [[Nauchandi Express]] and [[Rajya Rani Express]]. A weekly train goes to Chennai and Kuchuvelli. Daily trains connect Meerut to [[Bombay]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Jaipur]], [[Rajkot]] and cities in other states.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n;Metro Project\n;{{Main|Meerut Metro}}\n\nOn December 30, 2014, the Uttar Pradesh Cabinet had approved the proposed Metro Rail projects in Meerut, to boost the urban mass transport infrastructure in Meerut. The state government has nominated RITES Limited and Lucknow Metro Rail Corporation (LMRC) for preparing the respective detailed project report (DPR) and as coordinator, respectively. The development authorities would be nodal agencies for DPR.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/akhilesh-plans-four-metro-rail-projects-before-next-assembly-polls-115030400787_1.html|title=Akhilesh plans four metro rail projects before next assembly polls|author=Virendra Singh Rawat|date=5 March 2015|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729200728/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/akhilesh-plans-four-metro-rail-projects-before-next-assembly-polls-115030400787_1.html|archive-date=29 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref>\n\nThe metro project got the green signal from the divisional commissioner. It was decided in the meeting that the project would be along two corridors - Partapur to Pallavpuram Phase 2 and Rajban Market to Gokalpur village. The main stations on the first corridor will be Partapur, Panchwati Enclave, Rithani, Rithani West, Shatabdi Nagar, Devlok, Madhavpuram, Meerut Railway Station Road, Lajpat Bazaar, Begampul, Gandhi Bagh, Lekha Nagar, Pallavpuram Dorli, Ansal City and Pallavpuram Phase 2.\nWhile the corridor in the Partapur-Pallavpuram Phase 2 route will cover 20&nbsp;km and will have a total number of 18 stations in between, the 10&nbsp;km-long route from Rajban Market to Gokalpur village will have nine stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyoooz.com/meerut/126485/city-in-search-of-new-sites-for-metro|title=City in search of new sites for metro|author=NYOOOZ|work=NYOOOZ|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615232702/http://www.nyoooz.com/meerut/126485/city-in-search-of-new-sites-for-metro|archive-date=15 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Rapid Rail\n;{{Main|Delhi Meerut RRTS}}\nThe NCR Transport Plan 2021 proposed a rail-based mass transit system called Regional Rapid Transit System (RRTS) between Delhi to Meerut with the Shahdara-Ghaziabad section scheduled for construction during 2001-11 and the Ghaziabad-Meerut section scheduled for 2011\u201321.<ref name=\"ncr21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncrpb.nic.in/pdf_files/10modified_ch06transport.pdf|title=NCR Transport Plan 2021|pages=6\u20137, 11|accessdate=24 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321191743/http://www.ncrpb.nic.in/pdf_files/10modified_ch06transport.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the RRTS was reported to be proposed between Anand Vihar and Meerut with the project in its initial stages. The cost was projected to be around {{INRConvert|1000|c}} with the expected time of the journey being 45&nbsp;minutes.<ref name=\"min\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/soon-meerut-45-mins-away-on-rapid-transit/681630/|title=Soon, Meerut 45 mins away on rapid transit|author=Pragya Kaushika|publisher=The Indian Express|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=13 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921055420/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/soon-meerut-45-mins-away-on-rapid-transit/681630/|archive-date=21 September 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In November 2010, the train speed was proposed to be between 130-160&nbsp;kmph with stations at Anand Vihar, Sahibabad, Mohan Nagar, Ghaziabad, Guldhar, Duhai, Moradnagar, Modinagar, Meerut South, Shatabdi Nagar, Meerut Centre, Begumpul, Meerut North, Pallavpuram.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/anand-vihar-to-meerut-rts-7-of-14-stations-likely-to-be-in-ghaziabad/713690/|title=Anand Vihar to Meerut RTS: 7 of 14 stations likely to be in Ghaziabad|author=Pragya Kaushika|publisher=The Indian Express|date=20 November 2010|accessdate=13 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 December 2010, the NCR Planning Board, Meerut Development Authority (MDA) and [[Meerut Municipal Corporation|Meerut Nagar Nigam]] approved this system.<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/High-speed-train-routes-get-approval/Article1-638921.aspx|title=High speed train route gets approval|publisher=Hindustan Times|date=14 December 2010|accessdate=15 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211050142/http://www.hindustantimes.com/High-speed-train-routes-get-approval/Article1-638921.aspx|archive-date=11 February 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In August 2011, it was reported that the project tender had been awarded to Delhi Integrated Multi-Modal Transit System (DIMTS). The proposed system was to have dedicated trains between Anand Vihar and Meerut, which stop nowhere in between, and trains which stop at stations to be constructed after a gap of 4\u20135&nbsp;km. The reported stations were Anand Vihar, Vaishali, Mohan Nagar, Meerut Road (Airtel Cut) Morta, Duhai, Muradnagar, Gang Nahar, Modi Nagar, Mohiuddinpur, Meerut Bypass Cut and Pallavpuram with completion expected in 2017. The track between Anand Vihar to Dabur was proposed to be underground with the rest of the track overhead.<ref name=\"naredco\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naredco.in/news-updates-details.asp?id=3110&prYear=2011&xmon=Aug&st=1&links=|title=Delhi to Meerut in 45 Minutes|publisher=National Real Estate Development Council (NAREDCO), NEW DELHI|date=5 August 2011|access-date=6 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527105651/http://www.naredco.in/news-updates-details.asp?id=3110&prYear=2011&xmon=Aug&st=1&links=|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2013, the Union Cabinet of India approved the formation of the National Capital Region Transport Corporation Limited (NCRTCL) with a seed capital of {{INRConvert|100|c}}. The corporation is to take up the construction of the 90&nbsp;km-long Delhi-Ghaziabad-Meerut corridor on a priority basis (along with two other corridors) with planned completion in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Government-approves-setting-up-of-NCR-transport-corporation/articleshow/21017757.cms|title=Government approves setting up of NCR transport corporation|publisher=[[Times of India]]|author=Press Trust of India|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=12 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206193856/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Government-approves-setting-up-of-NCR-transport-corporation/articleshow/21017757.cms|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|author-link=Press Trust of India}}</ref> It was reported that the Detailed Project Reports (DPRs) for the three corridors were under the process of finalisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=97139|title=Press Release - Formation of National Capital Region Transport Corporation Limited (NCRTC)|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=6 January 2014|publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020024152/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=97139|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, problems were reported in the proposed alignment of the Delhi-Meerut corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/metro-projects-in-india-cheapest-in-the-world-458348|title=Metro projects in India cheapest in the world|publisher=NDTV|access-date=6 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106225450/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/metro-projects-in-india-cheapest-in-the-world-458348|archive-date=6 January 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2014, it was reported that the proposed alignment had to be changed due to objections by [[National Highways Authority of India|NHAI]] and the feasibility report had to be prepared again. The new proposed alignment increased the length from 90&nbsp;km to 106&nbsp;km.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/meerut-city-10980116.html|title=\u092c\u0926\u0932\u093e \u092e\u0947\u0930\u0920-\u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u0939\u093e\u0908\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0940\u0921 \u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0928 \u0915\u093e \u0930\u0942\u091f|language=hindi|date=3 January 2014|trans-title=Meerut-Delhi Highspeed train route changed|accessdate=6 January 2014|publisher=Dainik Jagran|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110185443/http://www.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/meerut-city-10980116.html|archive-date=10 January 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{See also|Meerut district#Demographics}}\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Meerut<ref>{{cite web|title=Meerut City Census 2011 Data|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/101-meerut.html|website=Census 2011|accessdate=21 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929122501/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/101-meerut.html|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|61.15}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|36.05}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.92}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhs]]|blue|0.6}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|1.47}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Christians]] (0.60%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (<0.09%).</small>\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, the '''Meerut Urban Agglomeration (Meerut UA)''' has a population of around 1.42 million,<ref name=\"cen11ua\" /> (comparable to kingdom of [[Bahrain]] or [[Trinidad and Tobago]]) with the municipality contributing roughly 1.31 million of it.<ref name=\"cen11city\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|title=Cities having population 1 lakh and above, Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011|accessdate=25 August 2013|publisher=Office of the Registrar General and Census Commissioner, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507135928/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Meerut Urban Agglomeration consists of area falling under Meerut Municipal Coorportation, Meerut Cantonment Board and 4 [[census town]]s of Sindhawali, Amehra Adipur, [[Aminagar Urf Bhurbaral]] and [[Mohiuddinpur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf|title=CONSTITUENTS OF URBAN AGGLOMERATIONS HAVING POPULATION 1 LAKH & ABOVE, CENSUS 2011|access-date=2017-06-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306023808/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/101-meerut.html|title=Meerut City Population Census 2011 {{!}} Uttar Pradesh|website=www.census2011.co.in|access-date=2017-06-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626002702/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/101-meerut.html|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This makes Meerut the [[List of million-plus urban agglomerations in India|33rd]] most populous [[urban agglomeration]] and the [[List of most populous cities in India|28th]] most populous city in India. The sex ratio in Meerut UA is 887, lower than the state average of 908; while the child sex ratio is 845, lower than the state average of 899. 12.99% of the population is under 6 years of age.<ref name=\":0\" /> The overall literacy rate is 76.28%, higher than the state average of 69.72%.<ref name=\"cen11ua\" /><ref name=\"cen11c\">{{cite web|title=Census of India 2011 \u2013 Provisional Population Totals \u2013 Uttar Pradesh \u2013 Data Sheet|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/up/Census2011Data%20Sheet-UP.pdf|accessdate=15 March 2012|publisher=Office of the Registrar General and Census Commissioner, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626232334/http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/up/Census2011Data%20Sheet-UP.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Meerut has a crime rate (total cognisable crimes under [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]] per lakh population) of 309.1, higher than the state average of 96.4 and the national average of 196.7.<ref name=\"crime\">{{cite web|title=Crime in India \u2013 2012 Statistics |url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |publisher=[[National Crime Records Bureau]] |accessdate=17 October 2013 |pages=28\u201329 |year=2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2017}}, Meerut ranks 328th(based on population), 189th(based on population density), 648th(based on built-up area) among world's urban areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|title=Demographia : World Urban Areas|website=www.demographia.com|access-date=2017-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013155105/http://demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|archive-date=13 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2001 census, the city ranked 2nd in terms of population in NCR<ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanindia.nic.in/moud/theministry/subordinateoff/tcpo/DMA_Report/CHAPTER_2.pdf|title=Area, Population and Density of Cities and Towns of India - 2001, Chapter II - Area and Density \u2013 All Cities and Towns|date=December 2007|publisher=Socio-economic and Monitoring Division, Town and Country Planning Organisation, Ministry of Urban Development, Government of India}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and 25th in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citymayors.com/gratis/indian_cities.html|title=India's largest cities / urban areas|accessdate=3 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119101044/http://www.citymayors.com/gratis/indian_cities.html|archive-date=19 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+Demographics of Meerut Metropolitan area (Meerut UA) (Census 2011, updated)<ref name=\":0\" />\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Metropolis\n! rowspan=\"2\" |City/Town/Village {{efn-lr|1=M Corp. = [[Municipal Corporations in India|Municipal Corporation]], NP = [[Nagar panchayat]], NPP = [[Nagar Palika Parishad]], CB = [[Cantonment Board]], CT = [[Census Town]]}}\n! colspan=\"3\" |Population\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Sex ratio|Sex Ratio]]\n! colspan=\"3\" |[[Literacy in India|Literacy Rate]]{{efn-lr|For Literacy rate, population aged 7 and above only is considered in India. }}\n|-\n!<small>Male</small>\n!<small>Female</small>\n!<small>Total</small>\n!<small>Male</small>\n!<small>Female</small>\n!<small>Total</small>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Meerut UA\n|Meerut (CB)\n|53024\n|40288\n|93,312\n|760\n|87.99%\n|79.48%\n|84.33%\n|-\n|'''Meerut (M Corp.)'''\n|'''688118'''\n|'''617311'''\n|'''1,305,429'''\n|'''897'''\n|'''80.97%'''\n|'''69.79%'''\n|'''75.66%'''\n|-\n|Mohiuddinpur (CT)\n|2811\n|2389\n|5,200\n|850\n|89.17%\n|69.63%\n|80.13%\n|-\n|Aminagar Urf Bhurbaral (CT)\n|3314\n|2827\n|6,141\n|853\n|91.01%\n|69.68%\n|81.02%\n|-\n|Amehra Adipur (CT)\n|2844\n|2641\n|5,485\n|929\n|85.68%\n|68.05%\n|77.14%\n|-\n|Sindhawali (CT)\n|2782\n|2553\n|5,335\n|918\n|79.92%\n|64.44%\n|72.53%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Meerut UA - Total'''\n|'''752,893'''\n|'''668,009'''\n|'''1,420,902'''\n|'''887'''\n|'''81.57 %'''\n|'''70.36 %'''\n|'''76.28 %'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"9\" |<small>{{notelist-lr|close=1}}</small>\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Historical Population Statistics<ref name=\"imp264\"/><ref name=kinship /><ref name=\"imp263\">{{Harvnb|The Imperial Gazetteer|1909|loc=[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V17_269.gif p. 263]}}</ref>{