-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|title=Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above, Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011|accessdate=25 August 2013|publisher=Office of the Registrar General and Census Commissioner, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017153124/http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />{{Efn|Provisional Data was revised and finalized when govt. updated 2011 census data on 20 May 2013.}}|| 752,893 (52.99%) || 668,009 (47.01%) || 1,420,902 || 22.31% || 887\n|-\n|colspan=6 style=\"font-size:88%\"|{{notelist|close=1}}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Literacy Rate (Percentage)\n! Year || Male || Female || Total\n|-\n| 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|title=Table - 3 : Population, population in the age group 0-6 and literates by sex - Cities/Towns (in alphabetic order): 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814033526/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=14 August 2004|accessdate=25 August 2013|publisher=Office of the Registrar General and Census Commissioner, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India}}</ref> || 65.22 || 53.17 || 59.62\n|-\n| 2011<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"cen11ua\"/> || 83.74 (+18.52) || 72.19 (+19.02) || 78.29 (+18.67)\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Mustafa Castle -- night shot.jpg|thumb|[[Mustafa Castle]] was built in 1900]]\nMost [[Festivals in India|traditional Indian festivals]], including [[Holi]], [[Vijayadashami|Dussehra]], [[Diwali]], [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]] among others are celebrated with fervor in the city. Notably, a fair by the name of ''Nauchandi Fair'' is held two weeks after Holi every year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nauchandi Mela |url=http://www.religiousportal.com/NauchandiFair.html |work=religiousportal.com |accessdate=3 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512080650/http://religiousportal.com/NauchandiFair.html |archivedate=12 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The fair, which started in 1672,<ref name=uptour2/> continues for about 15 days and is attended by [[lakh]]s of people. It includes events such as poetry recitations in Hindi, Urdu, Punjabi etc.<ref>{{cite book|title=Fairs of India|author=|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ol4Ndx9itz0C|accessdate=3 February 2012|isbn=978-81-87100-43-0|pages=16\u201318}}</ref> The [[Khariboli dialect]] of the [[Hindustani language]] is the dominant language for conversation with official business being conducted in either [[English language|English]], [[Hindi]] or [[Urdu]].\n\nMeerut is the headquarters of the [[Roman Catholic]] Meerut Diocese, which covers the districts of Meerut, Muzaffarnagar, Saharanpur, Dehradun, Haridwar, Moradabad, Rampur, Jyotiba Phule Nagar, Ghaziabad, Baghpat and Dhampur Tehsil of Bijnor district.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Short History of Meerut Diocese |url=http://www.ucanindia.in/diocesan-directory/home/diocese/meerut/130/ |publisher=UCAN India |accessdate=30 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014000826/http://www.ucanindia.in/diocesan-directory/home/diocese/meerut/130 |archivedate=14 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Nauchandi Mela (Fair) ===\n{{Main|Nauchandi Mela }}\n[[File:NAUCHANDI GATE MEERUT.jpg|thumb|One of the entrance gates of Nauchandi mela ground at Meerut.]]\nThe '''Nauchandi Mela''' is an annual [[fair]] held at Nauchandi Ground in Meerut.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://meerutnagarnigam.in/forms/NAUCHANDI%20MELAnew.pdf|title=Nauchandi Mela : Meerut Nagar Nigam|website=meerutnagarnigam.in|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215123911/http://meerutnagarnigam.in/forms/NAUCHANDI%20MELAnew.pdf|archive-date=15 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiaprofile.com/fairs-festivals/nauchandimela.htm|title=Nauchandi Mela of Meerut|website=www.indiaprofile.com|access-date=2017-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401114029/http://www.indiaprofile.com/fairs-festivals/nauchandimela.htm|archive-date=1 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The fair stretches for about a month and is organized by the Municipal Corporation of Meerut. It generally starts from the second Sunday after [[Holi]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The main exhibits are the artistic and religious rituals followed in rustic Uttar Pradesh. The fair witness more than 50,000 visitors every year. The [[Indian Railways]]' [[Nauchandi Express]] train is named after this fair.\n\nThe fair has a prominent history dating back several hundreds of years. It started in the year 1672 AD as a one-day cattle trading fair. The fair has been held every year, excluding 1858, the year after [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|1857 revolt]], which started from Meerut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meerutonline.in/city-guide/nauchandi-fair-in-meerut|title=Nauchandi Fair in Meerut, Historical Significance Nauchandi Fair|website=www.meerutonline.in|access-date=2017-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701060355/http://www.meerutonline.in/city-guide/nauchandi-fair-in-meerut|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSince then cattle trading has been replaced by a number of other activities. The fair feature shops for [[Lucknow]]'s [[Chikan (embroidery)|Chikan]] work, [[Moradabad]]'s [[brassware]], [[Varanasi]]'s carpets, rugs and silk [[Sari|sarees]], [[Agra]]'s footwear, [[Kanpur|Meerut]]'s leather items, etc. Meerut's own products like sports goods, scissors, [[gajak]]s, [[Nankhatai|nan-khatai]] are also sold.<ref name=\":3\" /> Giant [[rides]], [[Ferris wheel|wheels]], circus and various other recreational arenas where artists perform stunts, remains a big attraction of the fair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journeymart.com/holidays-ideas/festivals/nauchandi-mela-uttar-pradesh.aspx|title=Nauchandi Mela 2017 - Nauchandi Mela Meerut - Nauchandi Mela in Uttar Pradesh, India|website=journeymart.com|access-date=2017-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707062255/http://journeymart.com/holidays-ideas/festivals/nauchandi-mela-uttar-pradesh.aspx|archive-date=7 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Film and television ===\nMeerut is home to a film industry, which has a following in Western Uttar Pradesh and Haryana. The films are usually folklore stories or comedies or localised versions of Bollywood hits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naachgaana.com/2007/07/15/mollywood-dreams-audience-applauds-as-meeruts-showbiz-aspirations-take-wing/ |title=Mollywood dreams-Audience applauds as Meerut's showbiz aspirations take wing |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415100323/http://www.naachgaana.com/2007/07/15/mollywood-dreams-audience-applauds-as-meeruts-showbiz-aspirations-take-wing/ |archivedate=15 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The films [[Tanu Weds Manu]], [[Raanjhanaa]], [[Tanu Weds Manu Returns]], and [[Zero (2018 film)|Zero]] primarily take place in Meerut. The film [[Rajma Chawal]] shows Meerut.\n\nNotable people from Meerut in the film and television industry include [[Bharat Bhushan Bhalla|Bharat Bhushan]], [[Aziz Mian]], [[Mandakini (actress)|Mandakini]],<ref>{{cite book|title=70 years of Indian cinema, 1913\u20131983|author=T. M. Ramachandran|year=1985|publisher=CINEMA India-International|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q9rthUDKxyEC|accessdate=15 March 2012|isbn=978-0-86132-090-5|page=129|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522200019/http://books.google.com/books?id=Q9rthUDKxyEC|archive-date=22 May 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Achint Kaur]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Playing historical character is not easy: Achint Kaur |publisher=Indo-Asian News Service |place=Mumbai |date=31 December 2010 |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20100165067 |accessdate=15 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314201937/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20100165067 |archivedate=14 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"stars\"/> [[Kailash Kher]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kailashkher.com/bio.php |title=Biography \u2013 Kailash Kher |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518002435/http://www.kailashkher.com/bio.php |archivedate=18 May 2012 }}</ref> [[Chitrangada Singh]],<ref name=\"stars\"/><ref name=midday/> [[Vishal Bhardwaj]],<ref name=\"stars\">{{cite news|title=Stars on the horizon|author=Sandeep Rai|newspaper=Meerut Plus, [[Times of India]]|date=15 August 2012}}</ref> [[Deepti Bhatnagar]]<ref name=\"stars\"/><ref name=\"midday\">{{cite news|title=Vishal Bhardwaj mentors Chitrangada |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/mar/200310-Anirudh-Ruhela-mentors-chitrangada.htm |publisher=Mid-day |date=20 March 2012 |place=Mumbai |accessdate=15 March 2012 |archivedate=5 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405000705/http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/mar/200310-vishal-bhardwaj-mentors-chitrangada.htm |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Vishal Bhardwaj: Glamsham.com |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/interviews/vishal_bharadwaj1.asp |accessdate=15 March 2012 |archivedate=30 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530053726/http://www.glamsham.com/movies/interviews/vishal_bharadwaj1.asp |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and [[Pravesh Rana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-26/news-interviews/34083823_1_pravesh-rana-tigmanshu-dhulia-bigg-boss|title=Pravesh toes the family line|publisher=Times of India|date=26 September 2012|accessdate=14 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231060423/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-26/news-interviews/34083823_1_pravesh-rana-tigmanshu-dhulia-bigg-boss|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|List of educational institutions in Meerut district}}\nMeerut is an education hub of Western Uttar Pradesh with near about four or five universities, approximately 50 engineering colleges, 23 management colleges, seven pharmacy colleges, four colleges offering hotel management, one college offering fashion design, over 150 academic colleges and over 50 schools. The city is home to [[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]] (formerly Meerut University), [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel University of Agriculture and Technology]], [[Swami Vivekanand Subharti University]], [[Shobhit University]] and IIMT University. The city has one government-run engineering college, [[Sir Chhotu Ram Institute of Engineering and Technology]], a constituent college of Chaudhary Charan Singh University. There are schools affiliated to recognized boards such as [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]], [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]], [[International Baccalaureate|IB]] and the state board. One such school is the St. John's Sr. Sec School (established by [[Begum Samru]]) which is over 130 years old, also the first IB school in Uttar Pradesh was Vidya Global school.\n\n[[IIMT Engineering College which is now called as IIMT University]] is the oldest engineering institute of Meerut district. It was established in the year 1997.\n\n[[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]] (CCSU) is a public and state university which has many degree colleges affiliated to it. They fall in two divisions: [[Saharanpur]] and Meerut with nine districts including [[Saharanpur]], Meerut, [[Muzaffarnagar]], [[Shamli]], [[Gautam Budh Nagar]], [[Bagpat]], [[Hapur]], [[Bulandshahr]] and [[Ghaziabad district, India|Ghaziabad]] administered by Vice-Chancellor and Registrar (PCS officer).\nThe Indian Film and Television Institute is located at the western bypass of the city. The city has three medical colleges: [[Lala Lajpat Rai Memorial Medical College]], [[Subharti Medical College]] and [[Mulayam Singh Yadav Medical College & Hospital]].\n\nThe nearest government university which offers degrees in Engineering, Science, Management and Humanities is [[Gautam Buddha University]] located in [[Greater Noida]].\n\n==Media==\nMeerut is becoming a media centre, as journalists from all over [[Uttar Pradesh]] and other Indian states are working in Meerut. Radio stations shared with Delhi are [[Radio City (Indian radio station)|Radio City]] 91.1&nbsp;MHz, [[Big FM (Indian radio station)|Big FM]] 92.7&nbsp;MHz, [[Red FM (India)|Red FM]] 93.5&nbsp;MHz, [[Radio One (India)|Radio One]] 94.3&nbsp;MHz, Hit 95 (95&nbsp;MHz), [[Radio Mirchi]] 98.3&nbsp;MHz, [[AIR FM Rainbow]] 102.6&nbsp;MHz, [[Meow FM]] 104.8&nbsp;MHz, [[AIR FM Gold]] 106.4&nbsp;MHz. [[Radio IIMT]] (90.4&nbsp;MHz)<ref name=\"Radio IIMT\">[[Radio IIMT]]</ref> is the only radio station located in the city. The Hindi-language daily newspapers [[Hindustan (newspaper)]],  [[Rajasthan Patrika]], [[Dainik Jagran]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Dainik Jagran:About Us |url=http://www6.jagran.com/about/districts.htm |accessdate=3 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108034958/http://www6.jagran.com/about/districts.htm |archivedate=8 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Amar Ujala]],Dainik Janwani, The Hindu, Rashtrasewa, Dainik Jagran iNext are published from the city. The English daily [[Times of India]], Meerut edition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/56822_toi-launches-editions-in-agra-bareli-meerut-dehradun.html|title=TOI launches editions in Agra, Bareli, Meerut, Dehradun|author=Abid Hasan|date=5 Aug 2014|access-date=11 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806171004/http://www.exchange4media.com/56822_toi-launches-editions-in-agra-bareli-meerut-dehradun.html|archive-date=6 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the English language supplement HT City, Meerut with [[Hindustan Times]] is also published there. Moneymakers, an English daily is also published there. Asian Express, Hindi newspaper and news magazine Citizen of the World are also published there.\n\n== Sports Industries ==\nMeerut is one of the prominent Center in the country besides [[Jalandhar]] for the manufacture of sports goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/meerut/Bat-like-Meerut/articleshow/40067844.cms|title=Bat like Meerut - Times of India|access-date=2016-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108043157/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/meerut/Bat-like-Meerut/articleshow/40067844.cms|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are numerous sports companies in the city especially for cricket namely [[Sareen Sports Industries|SS]], SF, [[Sanspareils Greenlands|SG]], BDM. Players like [[MS Dhoni]], [[Virender Sehwag]], [[Yuvraj Singh]], [[Kieron Pollard]], [[Virat Kohli]], [[Kumar Sangakkara]] and many others have used bats made in Meerut{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}.\n\n==Tourist destinations==\n[[File:Ashtapad Hastinapur.jpg|thumb|Ashtapad Jain temple, Hastinapur NCR]]\n[[File:Agarnath Temple at 2nd Navratri night.jpg|right|thumb|Augarnath Temple at 2nd Navratri night]]\n[[File:Statue of Mangal Pandey at Shaheed Smarak Meerut.jpg|thumb|Statue of Mangal Pandey at Martyr's Memorial]]\n\nTourist destinations in and around Meerut include:\n* '''[[Digamber Jain Mandir Hastinapur]]''' \u2013 Located on the banks of the old ravine of Ganges, Hastinapur NCR is considered one of the holiest places on earth by Jains. It is believed to be the birthplace of three Jain Tirthankaras. There are many ancient Jain temples in Hastinapur NCR. Shri Digamber Jain Mandir, Jambudweep, Kailash Parvat Rachna, Shwetambar Jain Temple are the main and famous temples in Hastinapur NCR. Apart from Jain temples, Pandeshwar temple, Historical Gurdwara and [[Hastinapur Sanctuary]] are worth being seen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamarameerut.com/details.aspx?id=81|title=HugeDomains.com - Hamarameerut.com is for sale (Hamarameerut)|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n* '''Shahi Jama Masjid''' \u2013 The Jama Masjid was built by Hasan Mahdi, [[Mahmud of Ghazni|Sultan Mahmud Ghaznavi]]'s [[Vizier|Wazir]] (=Chief Minister) in 1019 AD (older than the [[Qutb Minar]]).<ref name=off/><ref name=\"imp265\">{{Harvnb|The Imperial Gazetteer|1909|loc=[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V17_271.gif p. 265]}}</ref> It is considered the first [[Masjid]] in [[North India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/north-india-s-first-mosque-going-strong-after-999-years/story-jPfLPas0NYQVTpLYE6YvIN.html|title=North India's first mosque going strong after 999 years}}</ref> Although it was restored by [[Humayun]],<ref name=off/><ref name=\"imp265\"/> it is one of the oldest mosques in India. Some believe that the first North Indian Mosque is [[Qutb Minar complex|Quwwat/Qubbat ul Islam]] in Delhi and then [[Adhai Din Ka Jhonpra]] in Ajmer.\n* '''St. John's Church''' \u2013 This church was established by Chaplain the Reverend Henry Fisher on behalf of the [[East India Company]] in 1819 in the cantonment area and was completed in 1822.<ref name=off/><ref name=\"uptour2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.up-tourism.com/valour.htm|title=The first war of Indian independence \u2013 Uttar Pradesh Tourism|archivedate=7 October 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007081637/http://www.up-tourism.com/valour.htm}}</ref> It is considered one of the oldest churches in North India. The Church was dedicated to the people by Bishop Wilson. It has a seating capacity of 10,000 people.<ref name=off/> During the war of 1857, this church was the scene of heavy fighting between Indians and the British forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india9.com/i9show/St-John's-Church-22539.htm|title=St John's Church|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214825/http://www.india9.com/i9show/St-John's-Church-22539.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Augarnath Temple''' \u2013 This temple (also known as Kalipaltan Mandir locally) is located at the site where the soldiers of the war of 1857 planned their operations. The temple also houses a memorial built to honour the martyrs of the revolt of 1857, [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]. The old temple has been replaced by a modern version.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbmeerut.org.in/heritage_sities.html |title=Cantonment Board Meerut Official Website \u2013 Heritage Sites |access-date=18 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202180144/http://cbmeerut.org.in/heritage_sities.html |archive-date=2 February 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Martyr's Memorial''' ({{lang-hi|\u0936\u0939\u0940\u0926 \u0938\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0930\u0915}} ''Shaheed Smarak''): The memorial is a {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=off|lk=off}} high pillar of marble situated at Bhainsali. Functions are organised at the memorial around the [[Public holidays in India#National holidays|national holidays of India]].<ref name=\"mdat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mdameerut.org.in/Major_Attractions.aspx |title=Major Attractions |publisher=Meerut Development Authority |accessdate=14 March 2012 |archivedate=12 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312000944/http://www.mdameerut.org.in/Major_Attractions.aspx |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The memorial complex also houses the Government Freedom Struggle Museum which is dedicated to the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|first war of Indian independence]].<ref name=\"uptour\"/>\n[[File:An Entrance to Gandhi Bagh Meerut Cantt.jpg|right|thumb|200px|An entrance to Gandhi Bagh]]\n* '''Gandhi Bagh''' \u2013 This centrally located garden has a very beautiful and serene environment. Locally known as \"Company Garden\", it has been present since before independence, when it got renamed to its current name. It runs a musical fountain show every evening. The park also houses a small water storage chamber and motor which is noted to have been removed from the [[Red Fort]] in Delhi and erected here. Earlier, the garden used to have multiple entrances, similar to the one shown in the image, which were always kept open, and there was no entry fee. But now, only one entrance is kept open and a ticketing system with nominal charges has been put in place.\n* '''Shahpeer's Mausoleum''' ({{lang-hi|\u0936\u093e\u0939\u092a\u0940\u0930 \u0915\u0940 \u0926\u0930\u0917\u093e\u0939}} ''Shahpeer ki dargah'') \u2013 This is a Mughal mausoleum erected by the empress [[Nur Jahan]] in 1628 in honour of a local Muslim Hazrat Shahpeer.<ref name=\"imp265\"/><ref name=jps>{{cite web|title=Revised Draft Report \u2013 Volume 2 for Preparing a 'Master Plan for Development of Tourism in the U.P. NCR' |url=http://www.up-tourism.com/tender/revised_draft_report_volume_II.pdf |author=JPS Associates |publisher=Uttar Pradesh Tourism |accessdate=15 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624193627/http://www.up-tourism.com/tender/revised_draft_report_volume_II.pdf |archivedate=24 June 2013 }}</ref> It is a red stone structure that was partly built and is incomplete till date.<ref name=jps/> The tomb is adorned by intricate Nakkashi (stone painting). There is no roof on the main tomb. It is said{{who|date=March 2011}} that Shahpeer was the teacher of Mughal Emperor [[Jehangir]]. The tomb is listed by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] as a national heritage monument.<ref name=\"uptour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/meerut/places_of_interest.htm |title=Places of interest \u2013 Meerut \u2013 Uttar Pradesh tourism |accessdate=14 March 2012 |archivedate=9 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155410/http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/meerut/places_of_interest.htm |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=asi>{{cite web|title=List of Ancient Monuments and Archaeological Sites and Remains of Agra|url=http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_alphalist_uttarpradesh_agra.asp|publisher=[[Archaeological Survey of India]]|accessdate=25 March 2011|page=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721180402/http://www.asi.nic.in/asi_monu_alphalist_uttarpradesh_agra.asp|archive-date=21 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Shahi Eid Gaah''' ({{lang-hi|\u0936\u093e\u0939\u0940 \u0908\u0926\u0917\u093e\u0939}}) \u2013 It was built by [[Nasiruddin Mahmud (grandson of Iltutmish)|Nasiruddin Mahmud]], the youngest son of [[Iltutmish]], and the eighth Sultan of the [[Delhi Sultanate]]. It is about six hundred years old and has a capacity of about one lac people to offer prayers (Namaz) on [[Eid ul-Fitr|Eid]]. There is Nakkashi on the walls of Eidgah which reflects the Sulatani Gulam era.\n* '''Parikshitgarh Fort''' \u2013 The place is associated with and derives its name from King Parikshit of Hastinapur NCR (the grandson of Arjuna). The fort was built by Parikshit and restored by [[Gurjar]] [[Raja Nain Singh]] in the eighteenth century.<ref name=\"Homepage\"/><ref name=\"off\"/>\n* '''Dargah of Baley Miyan''' ({{lang-hi|\u092c\u0932\u0947 \u092e\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0901 \u0915\u0940 \u0926\u0930\u0917\u093e\u0939}} ''Bale Miyan ki Dargah'') \u2013 This dargah was built by [[Qutb-ud-din Aybak]] in 1194 in the memory of [[Ghazi Saiyyad Salar Masud]] (known locally as Baley Miyan).<ref name=off/><ref>{{cite book|title=The foundations of the composite culture in India|author=Malika Mohammada|year=2007|publisher=Aakar Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dwzbYvQszf4C|isbn=978-81-89833-18-3|page=219|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103040834/http://books.google.com/books?id=dwzbYvQszf4C|archive-date=3 January 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> An ''urs'' is organised annually at the Dargah during the Nauchandi fair.<ref name=off/> It is adjacent to the Chandi Devi Mandir, which signifies the [[Hindu-Muslim unity]].\n* '''Suraj Kund''' - This is a pond, built by a businessman Lawar Jahawar Lal in 1714. It is filled with water from the Ganga Canal. [[File:Suraj Kunda Meerut.jpg|thumb|Suraj Kunda Park Meerut]]It is surrounded by several temples, including the Baba Manohar Nath temple, which is said to have been built during the period of Shahjahan.<ref name=jps/> It is also believed that there are a total of five ponds (kunds) in India out of which Suraj kund of Meerut is the biggest.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} The pond was naturally filled with the sacred water but with time it evaporated and the pond was left all dried. Presently, the [[Meerut Municipal Corporation|Municipal Corporation]] has transformed it into a public place A garden, a park with walk ways and in center a statute of swami Viveknanda. The place is open for all round the year.  \n\nOther places of interest include Mansa Devi Temple, Baleni, Basilica of Our Lady of Graces, [[Sardhana]] and the Chandi Devi Temple which was built by [[Holkar]] queen [[Ahilyabai Holkar|Devi Ahiliyabai Holkar]].<ref name=\"off\"/><ref name=\"mdat\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Indian Rebellion of 1857===\n*[[Dhan Singh Gurjar]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://livehindustan.com/uttar-pradesh/meerut/story-up-police-will-learn-the-history-of-dhansingh-kotwal-2049684.html|title=Archived copy|access-date=18 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804140420/https://www.livehindustan.com/uttar-pradesh/meerut/story-up-police-will-learn-the-history-of-dhansingh-kotwal-2049684.html|archive-date=4 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Kadam Singh]], leader of a group of [[Gurjar]]s who fought against the [[British East India Company]] during the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9DU5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA131 |title=The Peasant and the Raj: Studies in Agrarian Society and Peasant Rebellion in Colonial India |first=Eric |last=Stokes |authorlink=Eric Thomas Stokes |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-52129-770-7 |page=131 |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621070102/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9DU5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA131 |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Films and music ===\n*[[Arun Govil]]\n*[[Bharat Bhushan]]\n*[[Kailash Kher]]\n\n===King===\n*[[Raja Nain Singh]], Gurjar king of Meerut district in the 18th century{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\n===Politics===\n* Dr. [[Laxmikant Bajpai]], Former State President, BJP, Uttar Pradesh.\n*[[Somendra Tomar]], [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] for Meerut South           \n*[[Ravindra Kumar Bhadana]], politician<ref>{{cite news|URL=\"2012 Election Results\" (PDF). Election Commission of India website. Retrieved Oct 2015. Check date values in:}}</ref>\n*[[Malook Nagar]], businessman and politician<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/noida/greater-noida-bjp-s-tejpal-singh-nagar-wins-the-battle-of-the-gujjars-in-dadri/story-SXv2Jy7lca1LXFFbVhLKrL.html|title=Archived copy|access-date=15 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807185929/https://www.hindustantimes.com/noida/greater-noida-bjp-s-tejpal-singh-nagar-wins-the-battle-of-the-gujjars-in-dadri/story-SXv2Jy7lca1LXFFbVhLKrL.html|archive-date=7 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>     \n*[[Lakhi Ram Nagar]], businessman and politician<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Arrest-warrant-against-UP-Minister/article14809322.ece|title=Archived copy|access-date=15 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629065453/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Arrest-warrant-against-UP-Minister/article14809322.ece|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>                              \n*[[Hemlata Chaudhary]], politician<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.in/uttar-pradesh/assembly-constituencies/baghpat.html|title=Archived copy|access-date=20 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820235226/http://www.elections.in/uttar-pradesh/assembly-constituencies/baghpat.html|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n*[[Shahzar Rizvi]], shooter\n*[[Bhuvneshwar Kumar]], cricketer\n*[[Karn Sharma]], cricketer\n*[[Praveen Kumar]], cricketer                            \n*[[Shivam Mavi]], cricketer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/604757|title=Archived copy|access-date=19 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140556/https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/604757|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n*[[Dharampal Singh Gudha]], oldest Gurjar athlete<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/videos/meet-116-years-old-dharampal-singh-gujjarworlds-oldest-athlete_1473477.html|title=Archived copy|access-date=15 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815232834/http://zeenews.india.com/news/videos/meet-116-years-old-dharampal-singh-gujjarworlds-oldest-athlete_1473477.html|archive-date=15 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*\n*\n\n==See also==\n* [[2006 Meerut fire]]\n* [[Meerut division]]\n* [[Meerut district]]\n* [[Meerut (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n* [[Meerut (Assembly constituency)]]\n* [[Meerut Cantt. (Assembly constituency)]]\n* [[Meerut South (Assembly constituency)]]\n* [[Hapur (Assembly constituency)]]\n* [[Kithore (Assembly constituency)]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|CDP|2006}} |title=City Development Plan Final Report - Consultancy Services for preparation of the City Development Plan(CDP) for Meerut in the state of Uttar Pradesh under JNNURM |url=http://www.jnnurm.nic.in/nurmudweb/toolkit/CDP_Meerut.pdf |publisher=Jawaharlal Nehru National Urban Renewal Mission, Ministry of Urban Development, Government of India |accessdate=30 September 2012 |date=August 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031161415/http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/CDP_Meerut.pdf |archivedate=31 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|CMP}}|url=http://meerut.nic.in/UMTS/projectsummary.pdf|title=Comprehensive Mobility Plan for Meerut City|author=Urban Mass Transit Company Ltd.|publisher=meerut.nic.in}}\n*{{cite book| ref = {{harvid|The_Imperial_Gazetteer|1909}}|title=The Imperial Gazetteer of India|year=1909|volume=[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/toc.html?volume=17 17]|publisher=[[Clarendon Press]]|place=[[Oxford]], UK|title-link=The Imperial Gazetteer of India}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Service and Adventure with the Khakee Ressalah; Or, Meerut Volunteer Horse, During the Mutinies of 1857\u201358'', by Robert Henry Wallace Dunlop, Pub. R. Bentley, 1858.\n* ''[https://archive.org/stream/chaplainsnarrat00rottgoog#page/n4/mode/1up The Chaplain's Narrative of the Siege of Delhi: From the Outbreak at Meerut to the Capture of Delhi]'', by John Edward Wharton Rotton. Pub. Smith, Elder, 1858.\n* {{cite book|last=Nevill|first=Henry Riven |title=Meerut: A District Gazetteers of the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh, Vol. 4|url=https://archive.org/stream/districtgazette00indgoog#page/n5/mode/1up|year=1904|publisher=Government Press}}\n* ''The Mutiny outbreak at Meerut in 1857'', by Julian Arthur Beaufort Palmer. Cambridge University Press, 1966. {{ISBN|0-521-05901-1}}.\n* ''Mutiny in Meerut'', by Vivian Stuart. Aidan Ellis Publishing, 1991. {{ISBN|0-85628-210-3}}.\n* ''Flashman in the Great Game'', by George MacDonald Fraser, 1975.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.npsin.in/place/Mahadeo Old Village Mahadeo]\n* {{Official website|http://meerut.nic.in}}\n* [http://meerutmuseum.com Government Freedom Struggle Museum, Meerut]\n\n{{Million-plus cities in India}}\n{{Meerut district}}\n{{Meerut division topics}}\n{{Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing potentially dated statements from 2001]]\n[[Category:All articles containing potentially dated statements]]\n[[Category:Articles containing potentially dated statements from 2009]]\n[[Category:Meerut| ]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Meerut district]]\n[[Category:Cities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Siddhartha Ghai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTourist destinations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meerut"}
{"title_page": "1919 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "The 1919 season of the [[Auckland Rugby League]] was its 11th. It was the first season post [[World War I]] and unsurprisingly it saw a resurgence in playing numbers with 56 teams across the six grades. [[North Shore Albions]] who had previously dropped out of the senior competition again fielded a senior side. As did [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]], who had dropped out during the 1917 season.  In addition a new club was formed, namely [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. They were composed of old boys of the Marist Brothers\u2019 schools.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Bros. Old Boys/New Club Formed\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17144\n| date = 1919-04-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190425.2.120.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> The senior club season commenced on the 3rd of May.\n\n[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] won their third consecutive first grade title, while [[Newton Rangers]] won the Roope Rooster trophy.\n\nAt the end of the season J.B. Cooke stated in a meeting that next season the ball would be rolled into scrums and forwards would have to keep their feet on the ground while the halfback was putting the ball in. These changes were to \u201cbrighten the game\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Visit of English Team\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nThe season was also summarised by the league as well. Forty-nine teams were entered across all grades. Sunnyside won the second grade, Manukau won the third grade, City won the fourth and fifty grades, while Ponsonby won the sixth grade. It was stated that the standard of play in the senior club competition was not as good as it would have been due to the fact that 19 of the best club players from Auckland were away for a large part of the season representing New Zealand in Australia.\n\n===Representative Season===\nThe Auckland representative team was only able to play one inter provincial fixture against Hawkes Bay after matches with Canterbury and Wellington were unable to be scheduled due to the busy New Zealand representative schedule. Likewise Ponsonby were unable to schedule a defense of the Thacker Shield for the same reason. An Auckland Junior team was however able to make a trip out to Napier to play Hawkes Bay and they were victorious by 12 points to 5. Auckland played a match in front of an enormous crowd at the Auckland Domain against the touring Australian side but did not fair any better than the New Zealand national side, going down by 32 points to 8.\n\n===Charitable Efforts and League Funds===\nDuring the war most of the revenue gained by Auckland Rugby League was donated to the war efforts meaning they could not make much progress financially towards developing the game and facilities. In 1919 they once again raised 75 pounds to distribute to local charities nominated by the mayor. They also put on a match at the end of the season to raise money for the St. John Ambulance Brigade. Due to the large crowds at some of the matches, including the match with Australia it was anticipated that the league would gain over 1,000 pounds to establish a fund for obtaining a playing ground. This would of course be [[Carlaw Park]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =An Eventful Season/Record Gate Receipts\n| page =10\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17291\n| date = 1919-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19191015.2.116\n| accessdate = 2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===Eden Ramblers No More===\nAt the Auckland Rugby League meeting on April 30 it was announced that the Eden Ramblers club had been disbanded. They had formed in 1911 and played in the senior competition from 1911 to 1913 before becoming a lower grade club until this season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Executive Body\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17149\n| date = 1919-05-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190501.2.121.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[1918 Auckland Rugby League season|1918]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=11th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n|years=1919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[1920 Auckland Rugby League season|1920]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==First Grade Championship==\n[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu's]] first grade team were to only last one round into the season before pulling out. Grafton also struggled to field a team when they lost players to the [[New Zealand rugby league team|New Zealand]] team which was touring [[Australia]]. In round 6 rather than default they were provided with players from the [[City Rovers|City]] and [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] clubs however they too did not survive to the end of the competition.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =North Shore V Grafton\n| page =7 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17188 \n| date = 1919-06-16\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190616.2.118.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] won the championship for the third consecutive season.\n\n===Final Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|8||6||1||1||99||48||'''13'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|9||6||0||3||132||68||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Maritime\n|8||5||2||1||123||88||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|8||5||0||3||96||67||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|10||